Peace outttt 2022!!!! 

Spent the last few days reflecting on this past year. Many words came up to describe it’s entirety but one resonated the most. Patience. This year I learned first hand that although the universe is conspiring for your greater good (or so I like to remind myself often) some thing are out of our control. The most important thing we can focus on is the now, the planting of the seeds and once again… the patience to watch it grow.

Things that didn’t work out were just greater things that were in the works.
 
Some of those things granted me more time with family and friends, a relentless pursuit of purpose and passions and a year of Malibu beach side livin’. Here’s to another year of going with the flow 🤙🏼🫶🏼
happy new year 🫶🏼

First week of 2023 〰️

Letting go of the idea of having a wedding seemed more difficult than going through with it and actually planning one. As daunting as the whole thing seemed at first, especially during the uncertainty and aftermath of covid, it felt like an opportunity to gather everyone from our myriad of chapters in life before us to celebrate life in togetherness. As exciting as this all may seem, the charade of actual wedding planning is quite the farce. An out of body experience, that begins with the trying of hundreds of wedding dresses. Finding something that feels like “you” when everything starts feeling the same. When what you thought you liked isn’t what you like anymore. I guess all I’m trying to say is this whole thing is a trip. A trip I’m undoubtedly and indecisively enjoying.

My dearest bee,

There are not enough words in this world to express what you meant to me. Loyal and loving friend, chosen sister and above all most incredible mother. I struggle to believe you are no longer here with us, I can still hear your laugh in my mind. It was the most beautiful laugh. You lit up every room. Your beauty was effortless and you were so damn funny. 

You were absolute magic. 

Lauren, our friendship and bond was like no other. You were the first person to pack a bag and leave with me on an adventure with a one way ticket. We would laugh and reminisce on all of our wild escapades, like that time we got stranded in Ibiza. We laughed things off, bought a bottle wine and ran into the ocean with no plans of ever returning home. We felt unstoppable.

When life got more serious, we made time for each other. You never stopped checking in on me no matter where I was in the world. You would come visit me in LA and we would pick up right where we left off. That was who you were. Kind, loving, understanding and always there for your friends and family no matter what. 

One of the last things you told me was how proud you were of me. Lauren, I’ll never stop making you proud. You showed me a love like no other and I will continue to shine that light into this world for you. I’m forever so grateful for you, my best friend 🤍

Navigating through life we often forget to check in.

We get so wrapped up in the daily reciprocities of work, relationships and success so much so that we often begin to neglect our core need for self care. Checking in on ourselves has a fundamental impact on how we continue to live our lives and how we affect those around us. It’s important to allow oneself to just start small. Not everyone finds solace in a yoga class or around a bunch of friends in a social setting. Some might need to write a poem or watch a sunset in silence.

Checking in really just means taking the time for what feels meaningful to you.

These past weeks have been difficult for me but I continue to find ways to check in, breath and start over. Self care is a powerful tool that I learn to choose everyday. I’m grateful for the small things that the provide the balance. 

This is your sign to check in too 🤍

With the ongoing historic strike in Hollywood hitting it’s 100th day today, I find myself especially grateful for the opportunity to be part of a indie film starting to shoot next week. 

As of right now that AMPTP has failed to negotiate fairly to solidify an industry that champions everyone within it. For those that don’t know, SAG-AFTRA launched its interim agreement program that allows independent productions with no direct ties to the AMPTP to continue filming, allowing cast and crew an opportunity to still work during the strike. In my personal option and as lover of independent films, these smaller films are an opportunity to show big streamers that we as storytellers don’t require a green light from big studios to create powerful and moving films.

I firmly stand in solidarity with the union and the changes that must happen in order to protect actors, writers and creatives and simultaneously grateful for truly independent films that give people the opportunity to continue to work. 

For more guidelines/do’s and don’ts please check out @sagaftra pinned posts and my stories.

Thank you @oscardelarenta for reposting these special moments. The very first and final dress I tried on my wedding dress journey, after 8 months and three fittings later when the dress was finally complete I couldn’t resist the matching veil too.

The construction of the gown accounted for over three hundred and fifty hours at the New York City Atelier. The Micro sequin and glass beads were hand embroidered to the individually cut and applied motif. A true work of art!

The attention to detail in it’s intricate design yet timeless and delicate construction had me fall for it, love at first sight.

The morning of our wedding was a precursor to the festivities in the day ahead. Albeit the ladies had a much earlier start to the day, 4am for myself to be precise, it was no surprise the champagne and dancing had commenced as soon as everyone was robed and out of the hair and makeup chair.

With my bridal robe I wanted to compliment the appliqué details on my gown so it was no surprise when I found the perfect @oscardelarenta vintage kaftan. As for my something blue best friends & bridesmaids, they undoubtedly kept my spirits high and my worries low as we toasted to a lifetime of friendship and happiness. The boys in similar fashion did the same on the other side of the hall.
